Mortgage Delinquency Rates

Jake Vick

4/20/2020

Executive Summary

Serious delinquency rate is defined as 90 days or more past due, including loans in foreclosure. Without the ability to forecast Serious Delinquency Rate banks are left exposed to increased risk and significant revenue losses. With recent changes in the global economy, it could be beneficial to forecast the serious delinquency rate. Based on the models tested and documented with in this report, Median Quantile Regression proved to be the be the best fit model with an 87.07% accuracy rate when forecasting 4 quarters ahead.

1: Serious Delinquency Rate

1.1: Overview

A loan is considered delinquent when a borrower does not make a loan payment on time. Most lenders allow consumers a grace period for missed payments to get their loan out of delinquency. Once a loan is delinquent for a certain period, it becomes at risk of going into default. The serious delinquency rate is defined as 90 days or more past due, including loans in foreclosure.

Parametric and Non-Parametric Models will be used to forecast delinquency rates. Parametic algorithms have a fixed number of parameters, computationally faster, but make stronger assumptions about the data. In contrast, a non-parametric algorithm uses a flexible number of parameters and makes fewer assumptions about the data.

Initially, exploratory data analysis is conducted to determine the structure of the data. Then, different models are constructed to fit the data and determine what variables are significant to the model. With recent changes in the global economy, this model will determine if the unemployment rate will be a good predictor of mortgage delinquency rates.

1.2: Data

All of the data used in this analysis was reported on a quarterly frequency. All data except unemployment has not been seasonally adjusted.

Each variable listed below should have a direct impact on delinquency rates. For example, if the unemployment rate is rising and property values are dropping, it is expected to see an increase in the delinquency rate. This is due in part to people not being able to pay back loans or they just walk away from a loan because of a declining house price.

Formula:

Delinquency ~ Unemployment + Personal Income + GDP + Home ownership + Property values

This formula shows that the delinquency rate is the response variable and the other five vectors are predictor variables.

Delinquency Rates (Response Variable)

Federal Housing Administration (FHA), U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), Conventional Loans, and All Loans as a percent of total loans are all included in the serious delinquency rate variables. This data is from the Mortgage Banker Association (MBA): National Delinquency Survey.

Unemployment Rate (Predictor)

Total unemployment rate (SA) was pulled from U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS): Current Population Survey (CPS).

Personal Income (Predictor)

Total personal income (Mil. USD) was pulled from the U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA): Quarterly Personal Income - Table 05 [NAICS].

GDP (Predictor)

Gross Domestic Product: All industry (Mil. USD) was pulled from the U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA): Quarterly Gross Domestic Product by State [NAICS].

Home ownership (Predictor)

Home ownership rate was pulled from U.S. Census Bureau (BOC).

Property values (Predictor)

FHFA House Price Index of Single-family properties (All Transactions) was pulled from the U.S. Federal Housing Finance Agency (FHFA): House Price Index Datasets.

In the first series of charts notice, there are no outliers in the data.

2.1.1: Correlation

The data set contains the Delinquency rates, Unemployment Rate, Total Personal Income, Gross Domestic Product, Homeownership Rate, and the price index for Single-Family Home. This section will test the correlation between each variable to see if there are any trends in the data. The closer to one the more correlated the values are.

Unemployment Rate is highly correlated with all the Delinquency rates. Total Personal Income and GDP are both highly correlated. They are both negatively correlated with Delinquency rates since when the economy is doing well more people can pay their loans on time. Homeownership Rate has a slight correlation with FHA loans, VA loans, Conventional loans, and Total (in order of correlation). Price Index: Single-Family Home has a strong negative correlation with the different loan types.

3: Parametric Model

Benefits of Parametric Machine learning Algorithms:

  • Fitting the data to a linear line is easier to understand and interpret results

  • Speed

  • Dont require as much training data

Limitations of Parametric Machine learning Algorithms:

  • Constrained by trying to fit just a linear model

  • Limited complexity

3.1: Linear Regression

Multiple Linear Regressions (MLR) were used to forecast the delinquency rate. The MLR model uses several explanatory (predictor) variables to predict the outcome of a response variable. As the name suggests, the goal is to model a linear relationship between the predictor variables and the response variable.

3.1.1 Linear Model (ALL)

This model has the respones variable set to Delinquency Rate for all loans while Unemployment, personal income, GDP, Homeownership rate, and home prices are the predictors.

Interpreting Outputs

Residuals:

  • The difference between the actual response value and the one the model predicted is called residuals. The output below is shown as a five-number summary of the residuals. When assessing how well the model fits the data, a symmetrical distribution across the points with a mean value of 0 is very important. The first model, fit_USA, fits the symmetrical distribution rather well.

Coefficients:

  • Coefficients represent the intercept and slope terms in the linear model. The estimate returns the intercept and the slope for that variable. Standard Error is the average that the coefficient estimate varies from the actual response variable T-value is a measure of how many standard deviations our coefficient estimate is away from 0. A large T-values show there is a relationship between the response and predictor. P-value of 5% or less indicates that the value is significant.

Residual Standard Error:

  • The average amount that the response variable will deviate from the true regression line is the standard error.

Multiple R-Squared, Adj. R-Squared:

  • R-Squared provides a measure of how well the model is fitted to the actual data. A measure of the linear relationship between the predictors and response variable. It is always between 0 and 1, closer to 1 the better the model.

F-Statistic:

  • The F-statistic is a good indicator of whether there is a relationship between the predictor and response variable. The further from 1 the better.
#Linear Model test 1 ----
fit_USA <- lm(XMBASDR.IUSA ~ LBR.IUSA + YPQ.IUSA + GDPQ.IUSA + XHOWNRQ.IUSA + XHOFHOPIQ.IUSA, data = USA)

Model Summary

The first model fits the data surprisingly well. The significant predictors were unemployment, personal income, and GDP. The model produced residuals that are normally distributed around 0, low standard error, and a close to 1 Adjusted R-Squared.

Testing Model

The code shown below breaks the original data up into training and testing data sets. This will enable testing of the models accuracy by predicting values and comparing them to the actual data. The Mean Squared Error (MSE) which, is the average of all of the squared differences between the true values and the predicted values will be used to test against the other models. When considering model accuracy, the lower MSE value, the greater the models accuracy.

#train & test
n <- length(USA[,1])
obs <- n*.8
USA.train <- USA[c(1:obs), ]
USA.test <- USA[obs:n, ]

#acurracy
fit_USA <- lm(XMBASDR.IUSA ~ LBR.IUSA + YPQ.IUSA + GDPQ.IUSA + XHOWNRQ.IUSA + XHOFHOPIQ.IUSA, data = USA.train)
pred_USA <- predict(fit_USA, USA.test)
mean((pred_USA - USA.test$XMBASDR.IUSA)^2)
## [1] 5.207131

The next step is to use the anova() function to compare these models to see which one provides the best fit for the data analyzed. Linear Model (All) and Linear Model (sig) are very similar, the only difference is Linear Model (sig) removed homeownership rate. This ANOVA will test whether or not including the homeownership rate leads to a significant improvement in model fit.

Interpreting Outputs

Below, the results from running the anova() function shows a DF of -1 indicating the variable dropped in the 3rd model and a very small p-value. This means removing the homeownership rate resulted in a significantly improved fit over Linear Model (All).

3.2: Logistic Regression Classification (LRC)

Logistic regression is used to obtain odds ratio in the presence of more than one predictor variable. The procedure is quite similar to multiple linear regression, with the exception that the response variable is binomial.

In order to make delinquency rates a binomial variable this section looks for delinquency rate movement i.e.Upward or downward movements. It is important to note that this model predicts movement not magnitude of the movement.

Classification Summary

Exploratory data analysis is conducted on some classification variables. This is done in order to identify potential predictors. Federal Funds Rate and a Recession indicator were added for this section.

Federal Funds Rate is lowered when the Fed intends to stimulate the economy. By decreasing rates incresase the money supply, with more money in the economy, consumers will theoretically spend more. With the current data range note that the Federal Funds Rate is skewed toward 0 meaning it will not be a good predictor.

The Recession Indicator only had 7 quarters where it was True and 52 Falses. Because of the limited True cases it will not be a good predictor.

All Loan Type Direction will be the respone variable with the same predictors in the Multiple Linear Regression.

One downside to LDA is the assumption that the measurements from each class are normally distributed. In the lda plot, note that the each groups distribution is not normally distributed. This will casuse issues in fitting the model.

ldaPred <- predict(lda_USA,CIDtest)

Model Summary

This model has a 16% accuracy. It misclasses nealry all of the predictions due to the underlying assumption that each group should be normally distributed.

3.4: Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)

In the Quadratic Discriminant Analysis it is closely related to linear discriminant analysis, where it is assumed that the measurements from each class are normally distributed. However, in QDA there are no assumptions about the covariane of each of the classes.

qda_USA <- qda(Direction~ LBR.IUSA + YPQ.IUSA + GDPQ.IUSA + XHOFHOPIQ.IUSA,data=CIDtrain)

Overall, this model is useful when predicting the direction delinquency rates will move over time but it will not forecasting the magnitude of that move.

4: Non-Parametric Model

Non-parametric methods seek to find the best fit for the training data while maintaining some ability to generalize unseen data.

Benefits of Non-parametric Machine learning Algorithms:

  • Capable of fitting a large number of functional forms

  • No assumptions about the underlying function

  • Performance

Limitations of Non-parametric Machine learning Algorithms:

  • Requires more data

  • More of a risk to overfit the training data

4.1: Decision Tree

In this section, a Decision Tree is used to fit the model. A decision tree is a decision support tool that uses a tree-like model of decision and their possible consequences, i.e.change event outcomes.

#Tree ----
USA.tree <- rpart(XMBASDR.IUSA ~ LBR.IUSA + YPQ.IUSA + GDPQ.IUSA + XHOWNRQ.IUSA + XHOFHOPIQ.IUSA, data = USA.train)
rpart.plot(USA.tree, yesno = 2, under = TRUE, tweak = 1.4, nn= TRUE)

#MSE
yhat <- predict(USA.tree, newdata = USA.test)
mean((yhat - USA.test$XMBASDR.IUSA)^2)
## [1] 2.943657

Model Summary

The Decision Tree is made up of 7 nodes represented with the blue circles. Below the node the nubmer shows the percetage of data that the node represents.

The Root, node 1, splits the data by unemployment. The root node branches off into 2 child nodes, node 2 and node 3. The root node determines if unemployment is less than 6.8% and breaks up the data accordingly.

If umeployment is under 6.8% move to node 2. Then ask if the price index for single family homes is greater than or equal to 68. If greater than 68 the delinquency rate will be 2.1% (node 4), else delinquency rate will be 4% (node 5).

If umeployment is over 6.8% move to node 3. Then ask if unemployment is less than 8.5%. If unemployment is less than 8.5% the delinquency rate will be 6.5% (node 6), else delinquency rate will be 8.5% (node 7).

The model returns a 2.9 MSE meaning the error rate is rather low.

4.2: Quantile Regression

While traditional linear regression models use the conditional mean of the dependent variable, quantile regression models use the conditional median or other quantiles. Quantile regression makes no assumptions about the distribution of the underlying data.

This models uses the mdeian of the dependent variable, which is indicated with the tau = 0.5 option.

q <- rq(XMBASDR.IUSA ~ LBR.IUSA + YPQ.IUSA + GDPQ.IUSA + XHOFHOPIQ.IUSA, data = USA.train, tau = 0.5)
summary(q$residuals)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max.

q$coefficients

##  -1.219304e+01   1.493183e+00   6.072646e-07  -3.578832e-07   1.422005e-02
qPred <- predict(q,USA.test)
qPred
##       48       49       50       51       52       53       54       55 
## 3.488821 3.329770 3.193122 3.199222 3.072615 3.173094 3.082882 2.968291

## 3.092667 3.358485 3.150132 3.228231 3.151150
mean((qPred - USA.test$XMBASDR.IUSA)^2)
## [1] 0.8828787

Model Summary

The residuals of the model are not quite normally distributed which would be bad for a linear regression, but in a quantile regress there are no assumptions. The equation will be similar to the linear regression with respect to the coefficients. The key takeaway from this model is that it shows the lowest MSE tested yet. This indicates a low error with the predicted values vs the real test data.

4.3: Local Regression

The idea is to fit a curve to data by averaging, or otherwise summarizing, data points that are next to one another. The amount of wiggliness of the curve can be adjusted.

Local regression is useful for investigating the behavior of the response variable in more detail than would be possible with a simple linear model.

LocalReg <- loess(XMBASDR.IUSA ~ LBR.IUSA + YPQ.IUSA + GDPQ.IUSA + XHOFHOPIQ.IUSA, 
                  data = USA.train, 
                  span = 0.85,
                  control = loess.control(surface = "direct"),
                  family = "gaussian")

LocalPred <- predict(LocalReg, USA.test, se = TRUE)

4.4: K-Nearest Neighbor (K-NN) Classification

K-NN is an approach to data classification that estimates how likely a data point is to be a memeber of one group or the other depending on what group the data points nearest to.

knn_test <- CIDtest[,c(2,3,4,6)]
knn_train <- CIDtrain[,c(2,3,4,6)]

knn_pred <- knn(knn_train, knn_test, CIDtrain$Direction, k=1)
table(CIDtest$Direction, knn_pred)
##       knn_pred
##        Down Up
##   Down    0  9
##   Up      0  3
mean(knn_pred == CIDtest$Direction)
## [1] 0.25
knn_pred2 <- knn(knn_train, knn_test, CIDtrain$Direction, k=2)
table(CIDtest$Direction, knn_pred2)
##       knn_pred2
##        Down Up
##   Down    1  8
##   Up      1  2
mean(knn_pred2 == CIDtest$Direction)
## [1] 0.25
knn_pred3 <- knn(knn_train, knn_test, CIDtrain$Direction, k=3)
table(CIDtest$Direction, knn_pred3)
##       knn_pred3
##        Down Up
##   Down    9  0
##   Up      3  0
mean(knn_pred3 == CIDtest$Direction)
## [1] 0.75

Model Summary

For K-NN there are 3 different models with verying fits. For model 1 it uses 1 neighbour in its analysis and each model increases the neighbours considered i.e model 3 considers 3. Increasing neighbours after using more than 3 neighbours resulted in the same predictions. The best fit obtained for this model was 75% accuracy.

5.1: Best Parametric Model

In the previous section it was determined that Linear Model (Sig) was the best Parametric Model to forecast Delinquency Rates.

Formula

The multiple linear regression equation is as follows:

\(\hat{Y} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}X_{1} + \beta_{2}X_{2} +...+ \beta_{p}X_{p}\),

Where \(\hat{Y}\) is the expected value of the response variable, \(X_{1}\) to \(X_{p}\) are the predictor variables, and \(b_{0}\) to \(\beta_{p}\) are the estimated regression coefficients.

Model3 <- summary(fit_USA2)

\(DelinquencyRate = -10.21 + (1.44*UR) + (1.48e^{-6}*PI) -(1.27e^{-6}*GDP) + (1.74e^{-2}*HomePrice)\),

where UR is unemployment rate and PI is personal Income.

Forecasting

Linear Model (sig) is broken out into 4, 8, 12, and 13 Quarter time frames. Forecasting out 8 quarters yields similar Mean Squared Error (MSE). Forecasting 12-13 quarters out gets more problematic as the MSE nearly doubles.

With an 84.14% accuracy rate when forecasting 4 quarters ahead, Linear Model (sig) has proven to be the most suitable option for predicting delinquency rates with a Parametric Model.

5.2: Best Non-Parametric Model

At the start of section 5, Quantile Regression was identified as the top preforming model overall.

The quantile regression takes a similar structure to the linear regression model, the formula for the \(\tau\)th quantile is

\(Q_{\tau}(y_{i}) = \beta_{0}(\tau)x_{i1} +...+ \beta_{p}(\tau)x_{ip}\),

This means that instead of being constant, the \(\beta\) coefficients are now functions with a dependency on the quantile.

q$coefficients
##    (Intercept)       LBR.IUSA       YPQ.IUSA      GDPQ.IUSA XHOFHOPIQ.IUSA 
##  -1.219304e+01   1.493183e+00   6.072646e-07  -3.578832e-07   1.422005e-02

Median Quantile Regressions formula is as follows:

\(DelinquencyRate = -10.22 + (1.49*UR) + (6.07e^{-7}*PI) -(3.58 e^{-7}*GDP) + (1.42e^{-2}*HomePrice)\),

where UR is unemployment rate and PI is personal Income.

Forecasting

Quantile Regression is broken out into 4, 8, 12, and 13 Quarter time frames.

The forecasting has a very similar sturcture to the linear regression. There is the same signifiant drop in accuracy when forecasting out 3 years.

With an 87.07% accuracy rate when forecasting 4 quarters ahead, the Median Quantile Regression has proven to be the most suitable option for predicting delinquency rates.
